## Plan

**Approach:** Add a self-contained bash guard `scripts/docs-reality-check.sh` that builds etude fresh into a tmp dir (never an ambient binary, no network), derives the authoritative shipped-command inventory from the cobra tree, and checks three things: (1) every shipped top-level command is advertised in README.md and docs/README.md and has a `docs/cli/etude_<cmd>.md` page; (2) no doc names a command that does not exist; (3) `docs/plans/**` has no stale "future/not-implemented" claim co-located with a shipped command name. Wire it into a NEW Makefile target `docs-reality` (separate from `docs-check`) and reference it from the dogfood Docs/Final-Review checklist. Keeping it separate is deliberate: README/BRIEF are currently stale (sibling bead etude-phase-prep.2 fixes that), so this guard WILL report drift today. Folding it into `docs-check` would turn the existing green check red on known drift before phase-prep.2 lands. `docs-reality` runs and reports drift independently; phase-prep.2 makes it pass.

**Source of truth (decision):** parse the cobra tree, not raw `--help` prose. The script runs the freshly built binary's `help` output but scopes parsing to the `Available Commands:`..`Flags:` block and strips cobra's built-ins (`completion`, `help`). Cobra's printed command list is the registered set from `internal/cli/root.go`, so it tracks `AddCommand` calls automatically. This is more robust than free-text `--help` scraping and avoids a bespoke Go helper / duplicating gen-docs.

**"A doc advertises a command" (decision):** low-false-positive, format-tolerant, and prefix-safe. For each shipped top-level command NAME the doc must contain an `etude <cmd>` mention (the literal token `etude <cmd>`, optionally backticked — the SAME context predicate the stale scan uses), NOT a bare word. Bare-word matching is REJECTED because the hyphen is a grep word boundary: `grep -wE "capture"` matches `capture-gate`, so a doc mentioning only `capture-gate` would false-pass the `capture` check (a real prefix pair in this repo). Require: an `etude <cmd>` mention in README.md AND in docs/README.md, AND a `docs/cli/etude_<cmd>.md` page. Process the inventory LONGEST-NAME-FIRST and match the full command token so multi-token/hyphenated names (`capture-gate`) are claimed before their prefixes (`capture`). Flag any missing of the three. Reverse check: every top-level `docs/cli/etude_*.md` page (ignoring `_`-nested subpages AND the `etude.md` root index page, which names no command) must map to a shipped command. No brittle exact-list/format matching.

**Stale-claim scan (decision):** bounded `grep -rniE` over `docs/plans/**/*.md` for phrases `not yet|not implemented|does not exist yet|are future|is future|future work|unbuilt|not built` ONLY on lines that also contain a shipped command name (`\betude <cmd>\b` or backticked `etude <cmd>`). Same-line co-occurrence keeps volume tiny (verified: surfaces BRIEF.md:351 "etude bench ... future work"). A literal allowlist file `scripts/docs-reality-allow.txt` (path:linecontent substrings) suppresses legitimate "discussing planned behavior" lines (e.g. capture-protocol.md prose that intentionally frames commands as planned) so the guard stays actionable.

